{
  "session_id": "session-0093",
  "session_number": 93,
  "topic": "if the boys are friends with a guy and his gf, but they breakup, is it not fair if they still hang out with the gf in a limited capacity. They were friends with the gf more than the guy.",
  "flavor": "normal",
  "discord_user": "koole__",
  "started_at": "2026-03-31T21:21:59.177Z",
  "status": "done",
  "rounds": [
    {
      "ts": "2026-03-31T21:22:05.423Z",
      "identity": "chairman",
      "response": "Holden Bloodfeast\nBroseidon, King of the Swole\nHasan Piker\nDavid Hume\nPippi the Pitiless",
      "model": "opus"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-03-31T21:22:17.763Z",
      "identity": "hasan",
      "response": "Friendship isn't a loyalty debt you cash in when a romantic relationship ends. If they're actually friends with the gf more than the guy, maintaining that friendship is just being honest about what the relationships actually are \u2014 and trying to force a \"you gotta pick a side\" choice is the guy asserting control he doesn't have. The only real issue is if someone's being deceptive about it or the guy's using the breakup to isolate her, which is a different, darker problem. Otherwise this is just people being friends with people they're friends with.",
      "model": "haiku"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-03-31T21:22:18.087Z",
      "identity": "hume",
      "response": "Friendship depth is observable fact, not a thing you reassign based on relationship status. They have a longer history with her, spent more time with her, valued her company more \u2014 those are data points, not sentiments they can revise retroactively because a pairing dissolved. \"Fairness\" here isn't some principle floating above the facts; it's contingent on what actually happened: they were closer to her. Unless the boyfriend can show evidence that continued contact harms him materially or violates some binding custom they explicitly agreed to, calling it unfair is just asking them to fabricate an obligation that doesn't exist in the observable record.",
      "model": "haiku"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-03-31T21:22:18.754Z",
      "identity": "fit-bro",
      "response": "Listen bro, you absolutely can stay cool with the girl \u2014 but only if you're straight-up with your boy about it. No sneaking around calling it \"limited capacity\" while you're texting her on the low. That's the weak move. You have the conversation, you own your position, and you set real boundaries together \u2014 that's what respect looks like. Halfway commitment to either side is just playing both of them, and that's a rep you can't come back from.",
      "model": "haiku"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-03-31T21:22:19.376Z",
      "identity": "critic",
      "response": "No debt. You were friends with her before she dated him and owed him nothing then\u2014the relationship ending doesn't create retroactive obligation to distance yourself from her to spare his feelings. \"Limited capacity\" is cowardice; either the friendship matters or it doesn't, and pretending it's a concession to fairness is just avoiding discomfort while getting none of the actual loyalty of either choice.",
      "model": "haiku"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-03-31T21:22:37.751Z",
      "identity": "chairman",
      "response": "ABORT: The debaters reached functional consensus in round one \u2014 every voice says the same thing with different seasoning. Maintain the friendship, don't be sneaky about it, prior closeness is the relevant fact. There is no genuine disagreement here to resolve across further rounds. The only tension was Broseidon's emphasis on transparency with the guy versus Pippi's position that no such courtesy is owed, and that's a minor stylistic difference, not a substantive crux. Continuing would just produce three more rounds of violent agreement dressed in different rhetoric. Verdict: stay friends with whoever you're actually friends with; if that's her, own it openly and stop wringing your hands about \"limited capacity\" \u2014 that framing is the problem, not the friendship.",
      "model": "opus"
    },
    {
      "ts": "2026-03-31T21:22:41.925Z",
